To visualize and examine the knowledge graph database objects, you must first enable the feature in your preferences. Click on your account


Go to the Database Objects tab


Enable RDF Named Graphs


You will now have the RDF Named Graphs view available. Click on it to view the graphs you have created


The DEFAULT graph is where content goes when it doesnât have a name. For more information, review the 
DEFAULT_GRAPHS and Named Graphs help page
.


Click on the kg_hotels graph, and open the graph ontology to see the nodes.






Run a query to find hotelsÂ that have an indoor pool.


SQL
Copy
SELECT *
FROM SPARQL_TABLE('
PREFIX ex: <http://example.org/hotels/>
SELECT ?hotel ?hotelName ?city ?yearBuilt ?poolLength ?poolWidth
FROM <kg_hotels>
WHERE {
    ?hotel a <Hotel> ;
<name> ?hotelName ;
<city> ?city ;
<yearBuilt> ?yearBuilt .
    ?pool a <IndoorPool> ;
<included_at> ?hotel ;
<length> ?poolLength ;
<width> ?poolWidth .
}
');



Further examples of creating SPARQL statements can be found at 
SPARQL SELECT Queries Using SPARQL_TABLE
.




